**Sec. 10101. Re-evaluation of Thrifty Food Plan.**  
The bill amends the Food and Nutrition Act of 2008 to require the USDA to re-evaluate the Thrifty Food Plan market baskets no earlier than October 1, 2027, using current prices and dietary data. The cost of the plan cannot increase as a result of this re-evaluation, and adjustments will continue based on the Consumer Price Index starting October 1, 2025. Household allotments are standardized using fixed percentages of the maximum 4-person allotment, ranging from 30% for 1-person households to 200% for households of 9 or more.

**Sec. 10102. Modifications to SNAP Work Requirements for Able-Bodied Adults.**  
The bill expands exceptions to SNAP work requirements, adding pregnant women, individuals with medical certifications of unfitness, and California Indians under specific acts. It standardizes enforcement by defining "noncontiguous State" and allows states to request exemptions from work requirements if they demonstrate good faith efforts, with exemptions expiring no later than December 31, 2028. States must submit quarterly progress reports to maintain exemptions.

**Sec. 10103. Availability of Standard Utility Allowances Based on Receipt of Energy Assistance.**  
The bill modifies SNAP utility allowance rules to explicitly include elderly and disabled households when determining standard utility allowances. It also adjusts how third-party energy assistance payments are treated for households with and without elderly or disabled members, ensuring consistent eligibility and benefit calculations.

**Sec. 10104. Restrictions on Internet Expenses.**  
The bill prohibits the use of internet service fees in calculating excess shelter expense deductions under SNAP, effectively removing internet costs from allowable shelter expense calculations for benefit purposes.

**Sec. 10105. Matching Funds Requirements.**  
The bill introduces a state cost-share mechanism for SNAP based on payment error rates, starting in fiscal year 2028. States with error rates below 6% will receive 100% federal funding, while higher error rates result in reduced federal shares (95% at 6–8%, 90% at 8–10%, and 85% above 10%). States with high error rates (above 13.3% when adjusted by 1.5) will see implementation delayed until fiscal year 2029 or 2030.

**Sec. 10106. Administrative Cost Sharing.**  
The bill reduces the federal share of administrative costs for SNAP from 50% to 25% starting in fiscal year 2027, while maintaining the 50% federal share through fiscal year 2026.

**Sec. 10107. National Education and Obesity Prevention Grant Program.**  
The bill extends funding for the National Education and Obesity Prevention Grant Program through fiscal year 2025, maintaining the existing authorization level.

**Sec. 10108. Alien SNAP Eligibility.**  
The bill restricts SNAP eligibility to U.S. citizens, lawful permanent residents, and certain qualified aliens (e.g., Cuban/Haitian entrants, Compact of Free Association migrants). It requires states to consider the income and resources of ineligible non-citizens when determining household benefits, ensuring proper allocation of resources.

**Sec. 10201. Rescission of Amounts for Forestry.**  
The bill rescinds unobligated balances from specific appropriations in Public Law 117-169 related to forestry programs, including sections on forestry stewardship and community forest programs.

**Sec. 10301. Effective Reference Price; Reference Price.**  
The bill updates reference prices for agricultural commodities under the Agricultural Act of 2014, increasing wheat to $6.35 per bushel and corn to $4.10 per bushel, effective for the 2025 crop year. It also establishes automatic annual increases (1.005 multiplier) starting in 2031, capped at 113% of the original reference price.

**Sec. 10302. Base Acres.**  
The bill modifies base acreage calculations under the Agricultural Act of 2014, extending the 5-year average period to 2031 and allowing additional base acreage allocations up to 30 million acres for eligible farms. It introduces a formula for allocating these acres based on historical planting and prevented planting data, with payment yields established for crop years starting in 2026.

**Sec. 10303. Producer Election.**  
The bill extends the producer election period for Agriculture Risk Coverage (ARC) and Price Loss Coverage (PLC) programs through the 2031 crop year. It mandates that producers receive the higher of ARC or PLC payments for each commodity, and clarifies that beginning farmers receive enhanced premium assistance for crop insurance.

**Sec. 10304. Price Loss Coverage.**  
The bill extends PLC program parameters through the 2031 crop year, including reference prices, payment yields, and enrollment periods. It updates the benchmark revenue calculations and adjusts the gross income limitation for certain payments.

**Sec. 10305. Agriculture Risk Coverage.**  
The bill extends ARC program parameters through the 2031 crop year, including benchmark revenue calculations, coverage levels, and payment triggers. It maintains the 10% benchmark revenue requirement for 2014–2024 and 12% for 2025–2031.

**Sec. 10306. Equitable Treatment of Certain Entities.**  
The bill expands eligibility for "qualified pass-through entities" (e.g., partnerships, S corporations, LLCs) under farm bill programs, including direct payments and conservation programs. It modifies attribution rules and excludes these entities from adjusted gross income limitations.

**Sec. 10307. Payment Limitations.**  
The bill increases the payment limitation for conservation programs from $125,000 to $155,000 and mandates annual inflation adjustments using the Consumer Price Index starting in 2025.

**Sec. 10308. Adjusted Gross Income Limitation.**  
The bill adds an exception for "excepted payments" (e.g., crop insurance, disaster aid) if at least 75% of a person’s or entity’s gross income comes from farming, ranching, or silviculture activities. This applies to payments received on or after October 1, 2024.

**Sec. 10309. Marketing Loans.**  
The bill extends marketing loan provisions through the 2031 crop year, including loan rates for various commodities and cotton storage cost payments. It updates formulas for loan repayment and introduces special provisions for extra-long staple cotton.

**Sec. 10310. Repayment of Marketing Loans.**  
The bill revises repayment rules for marketing loans, allowing repayment at the lower of the loan rate or the prevailing world market price. It introduces refunds for upland cotton loans if market prices fall below the repayment rate.

**Sec. 10311. Economic Adjustment Assistance for Textile Mills.**  
The bill increases the assistance rate for textile mills from 3 cents to 5 cents per pound starting August 1, 2025, extending the program through July 31, 2025.

**Sec. 10312. Sugar Program Updates.**  
The bill updates sugar program parameters, including loan rates for raw cane sugar (24 cents per pound for 2025–2031) and refined sugar storage rates. It mandates studies on refined sugar import regulations and allows for additional terms and conditions to prevent unlawful imports.

**Sec. 10313. Dairy Policy Updates.**  
The bill increases the milk marketings threshold for dairy margin coverage from 5 million to 6 million pounds and extends premium discount periods through fiscal year 2031. It also updates production history calculations for new dairy operations.

**Sec. 10314. Implementation.**  
The bill allocates $50 million in additional funding for implementing subtitle C of the Agricultural Act, including surveys and studies related to dairy production and sugar programs.

**Sec. 10401. Supplemental Agricultural Disaster Assistance.**  
The bill enhances disaster assistance for livestock, including 100% indemnity for predation losses and 75% for weather or disease losses. It introduces additional payments for unborn livestock losses and expands assistance for bird depredation in aquaculture.

**Sec. 10402. Livestock Forage Disaster Program.**  
The bill modifies the Livestock Forage Disaster Program to allow two monthly payments and expands eligibility to include 7 of 8 weeks of grazing in a 4-week period.

**Sec. 10403. Emergency Assistance for Livestock, Honey Bees, and Farm-raised Fish.**  
The bill adds coverage for losses due to bird depredation in aquaculture, with minimum payments of $600 per acre. It also updates honeybee colony loss calculations to include a 15% normal mortality rate.

**Sec. 10404. Tree Assistance Program.**  
The bill simplifies tree loss calculations by removing adjusted mortality percentages and increasing the maximum tree age for assistance from 50 to 65 years.

**Sec. 10501. Beginning Farmer and Rancher Benefit.**  
The bill expands crop insurance premium assistance for beginning farmers, providing 5 percentage points additional support for the first two reinsurance years, 3 points for the third, and 1 point for the fourth.

**Sec. 10502. Area-Based Crop Insurance Coverage and Affordability.**  
The bill increases the maximum coverage level for area-based crop insurance to 95% and raises premium subsidy rates from 65% to 80%.

**Sec. 10503. Administrative and Operating Expense Adjustments.**  
The bill mandates additional administrative expense reimbursements for crop insurance providers in states with high loss ratios, starting in 2026. It also requires minimum reimbursement rates for specialty crop insurance and inflation adjustments for administrative costs.

**Sec. 10504. Premium Support.**  
The bill increases premium subsidy rates across all coverage levels, raising them from 38% to 41% for the lowest income levels.

**Sec. 10505. Program Compliance and Integrity.**  
The bill increases the civil penalty cap for crop insurance fraud from $4 million to $6 million starting in fiscal year 2026.

**Sec. 10506. Reviews, Compliance, and Integrity.**  
The bill raises the funding cap for compliance reviews from $10 million to $10 million per year (indexed), effective in fiscal year 2026.

**Sec. 10507. Poultry Insurance Pilot Program.**  
The bill establishes a pilot program for index-based insurance for contract poultry growers to cover losses from extreme weather-related increases in utility costs. The program will be evaluated in top poultry-producing states.

**Sec. 10601. Conservation.**  
The bill significantly increases funding for conservation programs, including the Conservation Stewardship Program ($3.255 billion annually from 2026–2031) and the Environmental Quality Incentives Program ($1.375 billion annually). It also extends the Grassroots Source Water Protection Program and expands the Watershed Protection and Flood Prevention Act funding to $150 million annually.

**Sec. 10602. Supplemental Agricultural Trade Promotion Program.**  
The bill establishes a new program to promote U.S. agricultural exports, funded at $285 million annually starting in fiscal year 2027.

**Sec. 10603. Nutrition.**  
The bill extends funding for the Emergency Food Assistance Program through fiscal year 2031.

**Sec. 10604. Research.**  
The bill increases funding for agricultural research programs, including $175 million for the Specialty Crop Research Initiative in 2026 and $125 million annually for the Research Facilities Act starting in 2026.

**Sec. 10605. Energy.**  
The bill extends funding for renewable energy programs through fiscal year 2031.

**Sec. 10606. Horticulture.**  
The bill increases funding for horticulture programs, including $100 million for specialty crop block grants in 2026 and $5 million for multiple crop surveys in 2026.

**Sec. 10607. Miscellaneous.**  
The bill allocates significant funding for animal disease prevention ($233 million annually from 2026–2030) and extends various trust funds and programs, including the Pima Agriculture Cotton Trust Fund and the Emergency Citrus Disease Research Trust Fund, through fiscal year 2031. [end of text]


